    " \"cells\": [\n",
    "  {\n",
    "   \"cell_type\": \"markdown\",\n",
    "   \"metadata\": {},\n",
    "   \"source\": [\n",
    "    \"# Laboratory 3 - Moving average convergence divergence (MACD)\\n\",\n",
    "    \"#### dr hab. inż. Grzegorz Fotyga, prof. PG\\n\",\n",
    "    \"\\n\",\n",
    "    \"The goal of this lab is to implement one of the most popular indicators used by the stock brokers - MACD. It can be used to analyze the trends and to determine the best buy / sell moments at the stock market. You will test that tool on the WIG20 historical data. \"\n",
    "   ]\n",
    "  },\n",
    "  {\n",
    "   \"cell_type\": \"markdown\",\n",
    "   \"metadata\": {},\n",
    "   \"source\": [\n",
    "    \"## 1 Introduction - MACD indicator\\n\",\n",
    "    \"\\n\",\n",
    "    \"Moving average convergence divergence (MACD) is one of the simplest and most effective trend-following indicators used in technical analysis of stock prices. As the name suggests, the moving average convergence divergence tool is a comparison of the relationship between the two moving average lines of a historical price data.\\n\",\n",
    "    \"\\n\",\n",
    "    \"Specifically, the first line of the two-line indicator is the difference between the values of two moving averages (explained in section 2), and is considered the MACD line. The second line (called a SIGNAL) is a moving average of the MACD line. Intersection/crossing of the MACD and SIGNAL lines are often seen as buy and sell moments (see Fig. 1). Both lines are centered on a zero line, and will travel above and below that level depending on the strength and length of a trend.\\n\",\n",
    "    \"\\n\",\n",
    "    \"\\n\",\n",
    "    \"![Figure 1](macd_example_plot.png \\\"MACD example\\\")\\n\"\n",
    "   ]\n",
    "  },\n",
    "  {\n",
    "   \"cell_type\": \"markdown\",\n",
    "   \"metadata\": {},\n",
    "   \"source\": [\n",
    "    \"Example: let’s assume, we have the stock prices from last 30 days. The goal is to predict basing on that data the tomorrow’s stock price, using the technical analysis tools, such as MACD. Or to predict when the increasing/decreasing trend will change. In other words, to determine the best moments to make buying / selling decisions.\\n\"\n",
    "   ]\n",
    "  },\n",
    "  {\n",
    "   \"cell_type\": \"markdown\",\n",
    "   \"metadata\": {},\n",
    "   \"source\": [\n",
    "    \"## 2 Arithmetic average\\n\",\n",
    "    \"\\n\",\n",
    "    \"Average - the simplest and most commonly used average is the arithmetic one: sum of a collection of prices divided by the number of prices in the collection.\\n\",\n",
    "    \"\\n\",\n",
    "    \"Tasks: \\n\",\n",
    "    \"\\n\",\n",
    "    \"1) load *data_10_days.txt*\\n\",\n",
    "    \"2) plot it using plt.plot() function \\n\",\n",
    "    \"3) Compute the average value of the data using 2 methods: \\n\",\n",
    "    \"    * direct implementation of arithmetic mean (using eg. *for* loop)\\n\",\n",
    "    \"    * *np.mean()*\\n\",\n",
    "    \"    \\n\",\n",
    "    \"    Compare both results. \"\n",
    "   ]\n",
    "  },\n",
    "  {\n",
    "   \"cell_type\": \"code\",\n",
    "   \"metadata\": {\n",
    "    \"ExecuteTime\": {\n",
    "     \"end_time\": \"2026-04-17T11:58:09.039448Z\",\n",
    "     \"start_time\": \"2026-04-17T11:58:08.826413200Z\"\n",
    "    }\n",
    "   },\n",
    "   \"source\": [\n",
    "    \"import numpy as np\\n\",\n",
    "    \"import matplotlib.pyplot as plt\\n\",\n",
    "    \"\\n\",\n",
    "    \"file_path = 'data_10_days.txt'\\n\",\n",
    "    \"data_10_days = np.loadtxt(file_path, delimiter=',', dtype=float)\\n\",\n",
    "    \"plt.plot(data_10_days,'o') # graph with o\\n\",\n",
    "    \"# your code\\n\",\n",
    "    \"\\n\",\n",
    "    \"sum = 0\\n\",\n",
    "    \"for price in data_10_days:\\n\",\n",
    "    \"    sum += price\\n\",\n",
    "    \"avg_manual = sum / len(data_10_days) # the average of 10 days\\n\",\n",
    "    \"\\n\",\n",
    "    \"\\n\",\n",
    "    \"avg_numpy = np.mean(data_10_days) # using given fun\\n\",\n",
    "    \"\\n\",\n",
    "    \"\\n\",\n",
    "    \"print(f\\\"Average (loop for): {avg_manual}\\\")\\n\",\n",
    "    \"print(f\\\"Average (np.mean):   {avg_numpy}\\\")\\n\",\n",
    "    \"print(f\\\"Difference:             {avg_manual - avg_numpy}\\\")\\n\",\n",
    "    \"\\n\",\n",
    "    \"\\n\",\n",
    "    \"#plt.axhline(y=avg_numpy, color='r', linestyle='--', label='Average')\\n\",\n",
    "    \"#plt.legend()\\n\",\n",
    "    \"plt.show()\"\n",
    "   ],\n",
